    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Eugenicists of the early 1900s relied heavily on pseudo-scientific theories to justify their racist views. They claimed that certain racial groups, particularly those with darker skin, were inherently inferior due to their so-called \"lower\" intelligence, moral character, and physical abilities. They argued that these groups were more prone to crime, disease, and poverty, and that intermarriage between them and \"superior\" whites would \"dilute\" the latter's genetic purity. They also pointed to the supposed \"biological differences\" between racial groups, such as the supposedly smaller brain size of non-whites, as evidence of their inferiority.",
      "source": "target",
